{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"240"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/240"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.01,0.22,0.56,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111816"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45632"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111816"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of increasing pain and swelling in his left knee. He had spent an afternoon bushwalking and noticed the pain after that. Since then, the pain is worsened by walking and eased by rest. Over the last 18 months, he has experienced some stiffness in his legs, but these symptoms usually rapidly resolve. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 135/75 mmHg, pulse 80/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The only apparent musculoskeletal abnormality is an obvious effusion around his left knee. This is not reddened, tender, or unduly warm. There is some varus deformity, and extension/flexion is limited by pain. There is no joint line tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound","Bone scan","Sterile aspiration of the joint fluid","Plain X-rays","MRI scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor a 62-year-old patient with knee pain and swelling, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain x-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation. The Ottawa Knee Rules suggest x-rays for patients over 55 years old with knee pain to rule out fractures and assess for osteoarthritis, which is likely given the patient\u0027s age and symptoms. X-rays can reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation, indicative of osteoarthritis. Whilst the Ottawa knee rules are applied to trauma, they could still be applied in these circumstances, where unaccustomed stress on the knee after a period of bushwalking could still be described as a form of trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated initially due to cost and time, and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone scan\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary without suspicion of metastatic disease or infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EJoint aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is more relevant if septic arthritis or crystal arthropathy is suspected, but the lack of systemic symptoms and joint warmth makes these less likely. \u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for soft tissue injuries but is not the first step when osteoarthritis is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients over 55 years old presenting with acute knee pain should receive a plain x-ray as a first-line investigation.","Plain x-rays are useful in diagnosing osteoarthritis, showing features such as joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation.","The Ottawa Knee Rules help determine the need for knee x-rays in acute injuries."],"references":["Braun HJ, Gold GE. Diagnosis of osteoarthritis: imaging. Bone. 2012 Aug;51(2):278-88. doi: 10.1016/j.bone.2011.11.019. Epub 2011 Dec 3. PMID: 22155587; PMCID: PMC3306456. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22155587/","Longmore, J. (2014).\u00a0Oxford handbook of clinical medicine\u00a0(9th ed.). Oxford: Oxford University Press.","Gupte C, St Mart JP. The acute swollen knee: diagnosis and management. Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine. 2013 Jul;106(7):259-68. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23821708/","Ridley U, Ridley L. Imaging of the knee: Common acute presentations to general practice. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 Jun;49(6):344-349. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-10-19-5120. PMID: 32464725. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32464725/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"240"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T07:41:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T07:41:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"240"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111816"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"c